defaultThe 
defaultHighway Code
default on Level Crossings: rules 
default291 – 299
default291. defaultA level crossing is where a road crosses a railway or tramway line. Approach and cross it with care. Never drive onto a 
defaultcrossing until the road is clear on the other side and do not get too close to the car in front. Never stop or park on, or near, a crossing.
default292. Overhead electric linesdefault it is dangerous to touch overhead electric lines. You 
defaultMUSTdefault obey the safe height warning road signs and you should not continue forward onto the railway if your vehicle touches any height barrier or bells. The clearance available is usually 5 metres (16 feet 6 inches) but may be lower. 
defaultLaws RTA 1988 sect 36, TSRGDdefault 2002 reg 17(5)default293. Controlled Crossings.default Most crossings have traffic light signals with a steady amber light, twin flashing red stop lights (
defaultdownload ‘Light signals controlling traffic’ (PDF, 82KB)
default and 
default‘Traffic signs’ (PDF, 486KB)
default) and an audible alarm for pedestrians. They may have full, half or no barriers.
default294. Railway telephones.default If you are driving a large or slow- moving vehicle, a long, low vehicle with a risk of grounding, or herding animals, a train could arrive before you are clear of the crossing. You 
defaultMUSTdefault obey any sign instruct
defaulting you to use the railway telephone to obtain permission to cross. You 
defaultMUSTdefault also telephone when clear of the 
defaultcrossing if requested to do so: 
defaultLaws RTA 1988 sect 36 &amp; TSRGD regs 10 &amp; 16(1)default295. Crossings without traffic lights.default Vehicles should stop and wait
default at the barrier or gate when it begins to close and not cross until the barrier or gate opens.
default296. User-operated gates or barriers.default Some crossings have ‘Stop’ signs and small red and green lights. You 
defaultMUST NOTdefault cross when the red light is showing, only cro
defaultss if the green light is on. If crossing with a vehicle, you should
default297. defaultIf there are no lights, follow the procedure in Rule 295. Stop, look both ways and listen before you cross. If there is a railway telephone, always use it to contact the signal operator to make sure it is safe to 
defaultcross. Inform the signal operator again when you are clear of the crossing.
default298. Open crossings.default These have no gates, barriers, attendant or traffic lights but will have a ‘Give Way’ sign. You should look both ways, listen and make sure there is no train c
defaultoming before you cross. 
default299. Incidents and breakdowns.default If your vehicle breaks down, or if you have an incident on a crossing you should
